         <div type="article">
            <div>
               <head><title type="main"><hi rend="bold">SANTA CATALINA ISLAND</hi></title></head>
            </div>
            <div type="section" n="1">
               <p>
                  <supplied>[...]</supplied></p>
            </div>
            <div>
               <head><title type="sub">TO EXPLORE <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">SAN
                           NICHOLAS.</placeName></rs>
                  </title></head>
               <p>Perhaps the most interesting feature in the history of <rs><placeName
                        type="island" key="#i_chi">the Southern California islands</placeName></rs>
                  is the story of the "<rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">Lost Woman of
                        San Nicholas Island</persName></rs>," who was deserted and recovered
                        <rs><date when="1853">years ago</date></rs>. <rs><placeName type="region"
                        key="#re_lwcave">Her cave</placeName></rs> and place of residence has never
                  been found. During <rs><date notBefore="1898-09-19" notAfter="1898-09-26">the
                        coming week</date></rs> an attempt is to be made to find it, but the
                  principal object of the expedition is to survey the big Indian mound on
                        <rs><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">the island</placeName></rs>. It
                  represents the accumulations of centuries. <rs><persName key="#burnham">Commodore
                        Burnham</persName></rs> of the yacht <name type="ship" key="#sh_sandiego"
                     >San Diego</name> is to make the trip, and he will have as his guests <persName
                     type="author" key="#cho">C. F. Holder</persName> and <persName key="#ssm"
                     >Sidney Smith</persName> of <placeName type="city" key="#ci_pa"
                     >Pasadena</placeName> and <persName key="#edo">E. L. Doran</persName> of
                     <placeName type="city" key="#ci_la">Los Angeles</placeName>. <rs><name
                        type="ship" key="#sh_sandiego">The yacht</name></rs> will leave <placeName
                     type="city" key="#ci_av">Avalon</placeName>
                  <date when="1898-09-19">Monday</date> and will be gone <rs><date
                        notBefore="1898-09-19" notAfter="1898-09-26">a week or so</date></rs>.</p>
            </div>
